WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: I.V.M.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:48.520
[Amit Varma]: I

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:51.480
[Amit Varma]: take a shot at answering all these questions and many more.

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:56.920
[Amit Varma]: I aim to go beyond the scene and show you all the unseen effects of public policy and

00:00:56.920 --> 00:00:57.920
[Amit Varma]: private action.

00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:02.800
[Amit Varma]: I speak to experts on Economics, Political Philosophy, Cognitive Neuroscience and Constitutional

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:07.640
[Amit Varma]: Law so that their insights can blow not only my mind, but also yours.

00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:10.720
[Amit Varma]: The Seen and the Unseen releases every Monday.

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:14.680
[Amit Varma]: So do check out the archives and follow the show at seenunseen.in.

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:20.400
[Amit Varma]: You can also subscribe to The Seen and the Unseen on whatever podcast app you happen

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:22.000
[Amit Varma]: to prefer.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.520
[Amit Varma]: And now, let's move on to the show.

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:29.960
[Amit Varma]: If Donald Trump saw the way I lived, he would be very worried.

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:31.280
[Amit Varma]: Here's what would worry him.

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:32.280
[Amit Varma]: My maidservant.

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:37.000
[Amit Varma]: There's a maidservant who works at my place, and she comes every morning to wash the dishes

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:38.480
[Amit Varma]: and do some household cleaning.

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:42.920
[Amit Varma]: We pay her a decent amount, something she's quite happy with, and we get along well.

00:01:42.920 --> 00:01:47.280
[Amit Varma]: She has no complaints with my wife and me, and we like her work.

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:52.480
[Amit Varma]: However, if Donald Trump was my grouchy uncle, and if he was visiting for the weekend, he

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:54.680
[Amit Varma]: would have a problem with my maidservant.

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:56.400
[Amit Varma]: I can imagine what he would say.

00:01:56.400 --> 00:02:01.880
[Amit Varma]: He would point out that while we buy the lady's housecleaning services month after month,

00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:04.740
[Amit Varma]: she buys absolutely nothing from us.

00:02:04.740 --> 00:02:08.400
[Amit Varma]: In other words, we are running a trade deficit with her.

00:02:08.400 --> 00:02:09.720
[Amit Varma]: This is unfair, he would say.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:14.600
[Amit Varma]: Either she should start buying things from us, as much as we buy from her, ideally, or

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:18.040
[Amit Varma]: we should stop buying her services and do the daily cleaning ourselves.

00:02:18.040 --> 00:02:24.160
[Amit Varma]: I can totally imagine Trump shouting at me, you are being exploited, Amit.

00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:25.500
[Amit Varma]: Sad.

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:27.320
[Amit Varma]: But Trump would be wrong.

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:28.320
[Amit Varma]: Can you see why?

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:33.680
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:02:33.680 --> 00:02:37.760
[Unknown]: Our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science.

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:40.160
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:42.600
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:47.120
[Amit Varma]: My intro to this episode was inspired by an article Tim Harford wrote in the Financial

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:51.320
[Amit Varma]: Times in 2005, titled, A Trade Deficit with a Babysitter.

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:55.520
[Amit Varma]: Now, I don't have a baby, so I Indianized it a little bit, and I don't need to tell

00:02:55.520 --> 00:03:00.640
[Amit Varma]: you why it is absurd to think of a trade deficit with a maidservant as a problem.

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:03.960
[Amit Varma]: It is because all trade is a positive sum game.

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Both parties benefit.

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:09.920
[Amit Varma]: We get our housecleaning done at a rate we are happy to pay, our maidservant gets a remuneration

00:03:09.920 --> 00:03:13.780
[Amit Varma]: for it that she is happy with, otherwise she wouldn't do the job in the first place.

00:03:13.780 --> 00:03:15.880
[Amit Varma]: Both of us are better off.

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:18.680
[Amit Varma]: This is true even of trade between countries.

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And here's the thing, countries don't really trade with each other.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.000
[Amit Varma]: People do.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.240
[Amit Varma]: The US has a trade deficit with China, for example.

00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:30.560
[Amit Varma]: But actually, it doesn't mean that the US as a nation is buying anything from China

00:03:30.560 --> 00:03:31.560
[Amit Varma]: the nation.

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:36.200
[Amit Varma]: Individuals and corporations on both sides are trading with each other, and each trade

00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:38.200
[Amit Varma]: leaves both parties better off.

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:42.720
[Amit Varma]: The value that is created or saved goes back into their respective economies.

00:03:42.720 --> 00:03:48.660
[Amit Varma]: A trade deficit between countries is no more a bad thing than your trade deficit with your

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:50.140
[Amit Varma]: maidservant.

00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:53.760
[Amit Varma]: And for this reason, protectionism is daft.

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:55.840
[Amit Varma]: This is just basic economics.

00:03:55.840 --> 00:03:59.800
[Amit Varma]: Donald Trump disagrees, because he looks at the world in a zero-sum way.

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:04.160
[Amit Varma]: But I won't go into that in detail in this episode, because I already did a pretty exhaustive

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:06.920
[Amit Varma]: episode on protectionism a few weeks ago.

00:04:06.920 --> 00:04:11.600
[Amit Varma]: Episode 59 of the Seen and the Unseen deals with protectionism, and my guest, the economist

00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:15.480
[Amit Varma]: Anupam Manoor busted 8 common myths about protectionism.

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:18.800
[Amit Varma]: Check that out in the archives of the show at seenunseen.in.

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:23.760
[Amit Varma]: Today though, I have a guest who will take us into another aspect of trade deficits and

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:27.880
[Amit Varma]: Donald Trump's protectionist urge, the monetary aspect.

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:32.320
[Amit Varma]: Vivek Kaul is my good friend and a frequent guest on this show, as well as the author

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:37.240
[Amit Varma]: of the outstanding Easy Money trilogy, which has just been re-released by HarperCollins.

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.680
[Amit Varma]: Many of the insights he will now share with us are from that book.

00:04:40.680 --> 00:04:45.200
[Amit Varma]: But before I start my conversation with him, let's take a quick commercial break.

