00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:35.320
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene in the unseen, Vivek.

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:36.840
[Guest]: Thanks Amit for having me over.

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:40.800
[Amit Varma]: Vivek, this is going to be a tougher episode for you than usual because I've started this

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:45.920
[Amit Varma]: new custom of, from the last episode, of asking my friends personal questions about themselves

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:50.280
[Amit Varma]: so that the listeners can get to know them a little better.

00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:54.760
[Amit Varma]: So tell us a little bit about yourself, what's your background and how did you become a journalist?

00:05:54.760 --> 00:05:57.160
[Guest]: Where do I see myself five years from now?

00:05:57.160 --> 00:05:58.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and how do you feel?

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:03.080
[Amit Varma]: Aap batayenge hain, aapke zahin mein abhi kya chal raha hai, no no, seriously.

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:12.640
[Guest]: So basically, you know, I did an MBA in information systems, and I worked for an IT company, I

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:16.560
[Guest]: was a project manager there, for all of 35 days.

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:22.040
[Guest]: So the first two weeks, it sort of took me to figure out that I didn't fit in.

00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:26.960
[Guest]: The next two weeks, it took me to gather the courage to speak to my parents, primarily

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:33.680
[Guest]: my father, because he would have to continue, you know, financing me, and at the end of

00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:35.240
[Guest]: the fifth week, I quit.

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:38.520
[Guest]: I just stopped going, in fact, I didn't even quit.

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:47.240
[Guest]: And then I tried doing a PhD for three years, and after that, I sort of landed up in journalism.

00:06:47.240 --> 00:06:52.720
[Guest]: And that was also quite by chance because, you know, DNA had launched in Mumbai and they

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:57.680
[Guest]: needed a personal finance editor, and I just landed up and I got the job, even though I

00:06:57.680 --> 00:06:59.520
[Guest]: didn't know anything about personal finance.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:02.400
[Guest]: So that's how I sort of...

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:05.440
[Amit Varma]: And all the journalism that I've read of you, like I've been reading you for a few years,

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:09.240
[Amit Varma]: so perhaps not from when you started, and all of it has been economics journalism.

00:07:09.240 --> 00:07:10.240
[Guest]: I mean, what you specifically...

00:07:10.240 --> 00:07:15.520
[Guest]: Yes, so that economics essentially started once I went, you know, freelance.

00:07:15.520 --> 00:07:21.080
[Guest]: That was primarily because one is it, you know, allows you to sort of write on a wide

00:07:21.080 --> 00:07:23.100
[Guest]: array of topics.

00:07:23.100 --> 00:07:25.320
[Guest]: So you can make more money.

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:29.560
[Guest]: Personal finance, what happens is, you know, after you've done it for a couple of years,

00:07:29.560 --> 00:07:31.840
[Guest]: I mean, you're done, there's nothing more to it.

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:39.240
[Guest]: In fact, a couple of years, there's this great story about Scott Adams, the creator of Dilbert.

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:43.080
[Guest]: He once decided that he wanted to write a book on personal finance.

00:07:43.080 --> 00:07:48.280
[Guest]: And then he figured out that all of personal finance could be summarized in 87 words.

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:49.600
[Guest]: So he gave up on the idea.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:52.880
[Guest]: So you know, once you know that these are the four or five things you need to generally

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:58.160
[Guest]: do in order to manage your finances, after that it is, you're just rehashing, you know,

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:00.440
[Guest]: the same thing day in, day out.

00:08:00.440 --> 00:08:05.460
[Guest]: And you can probably rehash for two to three years, beyond that, it's a little difficult.

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:11.440
[Guest]: So you know, by 2007, 2008, I had already started, you know, writing more on economics

00:08:11.440 --> 00:08:15.160
[Guest]: and management and, you know, personal finance had taken a backseat.

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:21.560
[Guest]: And once I went freelance in 2012, economics became the main breadwinner.

00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:24.840
[Amit Varma]: And you know, there are plenty of economics journalists in the country, but one sort of

00:08:24.840 --> 00:08:29.080
[Amit Varma]: niche which you've almost made your own and one reason, in fact, why you're such an excellent

00:08:29.080 --> 00:08:34.160
[Amit Varma]: guest for the show, and I keep calling you here, is that you like to explain complicated

00:08:34.160 --> 00:08:38.240
[Amit Varma]: economic fundas in simple language, which your grandmother can understand, or your mother,

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:43.000
[Amit Varma]: as you said in an interview recently, was it like that from the beginning, or did you

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.320
[Amit Varma]: at some point while engaging with your readers?

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:51.800
[Guest]: No, actually, what, see, what happens is, and this is from the benefit of hindsight,

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:56.320
[Guest]: you know, when you when you, so I never studied economics, okay, I mean, I've never went,

00:08:56.320 --> 00:09:04.360
[Guest]: I mean, I've never gone to a, you know, college where, you know, I studied economics, my only

00:09:04.360 --> 00:09:10.520
[Guest]: exposure to economics was when I was doing my MBA, where, you know, in any standard MBA

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:17.080
[Guest]: course, has one subject, you know, one paper on microeconomics, and one paper on macroeconomics.

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:20.960
[Guest]: And that is, you know, you don't really learn much there, because, you know, my MBA at the

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:21.960
[Guest]: end had 72 subjects.

00:09:21.960 --> 00:09:25.720
[Guest]: So two out of those 72, you really don't learn anything.

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:33.600
[Guest]: So once, so when I first started writing economics, and this was for rediff, actually, and sometime

00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:42.920
[Guest]: in late 2003, early 2004, when I first started writing economics, it was more of an act of

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:48.080
[Guest]: trying to understand things myself, okay.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:51.880
[Guest]: And that sort of state.

00:09:51.880 --> 00:09:54.520
[Guest]: So you know, what has happened over the years is that,

00:09:54.520 --> 00:09:59.000
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, the older Vivek today is writing for the younger Vivek, who's just learning

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:00.000
[Amit Varma]: the subject.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.360
[Amit Varma]: Yes, I mean, you could say that, yeah.

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:09.240
[Amit Varma]: And since you're self-taught, in a sense, you're an autodidact to use that term in economics.

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:11.520
[Amit Varma]: Who are the writers which impressed you the most?

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:15.760
[Amit Varma]: And which are the books which you felt were most useful in sort of bringing about quantum

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:17.360
[Amit Varma]: leaps in your understanding, for example?

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:20.880
[Guest]: Okay, so you know, my problem is, I don't remember much of what I read.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:27.520
[Guest]: So I mean, I'll sort of some of the books that, in fact, an early book that I read,

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:36.120
[Guest]: and I quite liked it, was a textbook by C. Rangarajan and Bakul Dholokia.

00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:43.280
[Guest]: And they wrote this book in 1979, when Mr. Rangarajan was still teaching at IIM Ahmedabad.

00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:46.640
[Guest]: And that was just one edition of that book that ever appeared.

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:51.720
[Guest]: And you know, for the next 25 years, 30 years, they just kept republishing it.

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:57.200
[Guest]: So I learned all the basic economics there, you know, what is GDP, what is fiscal deficit,

00:10:57.200 --> 00:11:02.000
[Guest]: how is GDP defined, you know, the basic very, you know, what is current account deficit,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:06.240
[Guest]: what is trade deficit, and it was a brilliant book.

00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:11.080
[Guest]: The tragedy is, I lost my copy, and I've never been able to find it again, because I think

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:12.680
[Guest]: it's out of print.

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:14.760
[Amit Varma]: So that was...

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:19.160
[Guest]: So if any of the listeners have an old copy of the book, you can do a good deed to the

00:11:19.160 --> 00:11:20.160
[Guest]: world.

00:11:20.160 --> 00:11:21.160
[Guest]: Yes.

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:27.280
[Guest]: So that was one book that really sort of, then there have been a lot of, you know, I

00:11:27.280 --> 00:11:31.640
[Guest]: think Tim Harford writes economics in a very, very approachable way.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:34.360
[Guest]: His books have really been great.

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:38.120
[Guest]: Of late, I've been reading Thomas Sowell.

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:44.120
[Guest]: I mean, his books are just fantastic, because, you know, what he does is, and what is actually

00:11:44.120 --> 00:11:52.080
[Guest]: missing from most economics textbooks is that he relates economics to politics, society

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:53.800
[Guest]: and everyday life.

00:11:53.800 --> 00:11:58.400
[Guest]: And there, you know, I mean, I find it very, very funny that, you know, economics actually

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:05.040
[Guest]: gets taught in colleges without being related to, you know, the society and the politics

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:06.040
[Amit Varma]: at large.

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:09.560
[Amit Varma]: Thomas Sowell, for me, is one of the finest thinkers of the last century.

00:12:09.560 --> 00:12:13.640
[Amit Varma]: And even speaking in terms of textbooks, I think his two books, Basic Economics and Applied

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:18.160
[Guest]: Economics are both fantastic, in the sense that, you know, anyone can pick up and start

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:19.160
[Guest]: reading it.

00:12:19.160 --> 00:12:20.160
[Guest]: There are no graphs, there is no math.

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:21.160
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:12:21.160 --> 00:12:24.000
[Guest]: And it's not that, you know, personally, I don't have a problem with math and graphs,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.680
[Unknown]: but it does put off a lot of people.

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:28.680
[Guest]: And it's just fantastic.

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:34.360
[Guest]: In fact, before I came here, I was reading, you know, Basic Economics, and that's a book

00:12:34.360 --> 00:12:42.760
[Guest]: I sort of keep going back to because it just explains things in a very, very practical

00:12:42.760 --> 00:12:43.760
[Guest]: sort of way.

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:49.520
[Guest]: So, Thomas Sowell, you know, anyone who wants to learn economics and does not want to take

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:54.440
[Guest]: a full course or spend two years or three years in college, it's by far the best.

00:12:54.440 --> 00:12:59.240
[Amit Varma]: In fact, if I may give a recommendation to my listeners, another textbook, which is really

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:04.000
[Amit Varma]: good is Tyler Carvin and Alex Tabarrok's textbook on macroeconomics and microeconomics.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:09.680
[Amit Varma]: And they also have great video courses at Marginal Revolution University.

00:13:09.680 --> 00:13:10.840
[Amit Varma]: So check that out.

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:11.840
[Amit Varma]: Those are just wonderful.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:17.120
[Amit Varma]: Now, on Twitter, I promised your readers and my readers as well, that I would make you

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:21.080
[Amit Varma]: reveal something about yourself that no one in the world knows.

00:13:21.080 --> 00:13:22.680
[Guest]: This is the first time people will come to know.

00:13:22.680 --> 00:13:28.520
[Guest]: I mean, it's very difficult to come up with something, you know, which no one in the world

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:29.520
[Amit Varma]: knows.

00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:32.040
[Amit Varma]: Okay, let's say maybe your parents or your loved ones might know something, but the world

00:13:32.040 --> 00:13:35.680
[Amit Varma]: at large would be surprised by this saying, really, Vivek likes wearing lingerie?

00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:38.680
[Guest]: You know, something like that.

00:13:38.680 --> 00:13:40.880
[Guest]: No, I mean, I'm not.

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:43.920
[Guest]: So you know, lingerie reminds me of an old story.

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:49.720
[Guest]: And this was, I think, sometime 2007 or 2008 or 2009, maybe.

00:13:49.720 --> 00:13:57.080
[Guest]: And, and my grandfather asked my sister, in a very roundabout manner, which took my sister

00:13:57.080 --> 00:14:02.240
[Guest]: some time to figure out as to, you know, what did he really mean by what he said.

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:07.480
[Guest]: And he basically asked her, kya isko ladkiya pasand nahi hai, which essentially, you know,

00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:11.080
[Guest]: it was his way of asking whether, you know, I'm gay, so.

00:14:11.080 --> 00:14:17.080
[Amit Varma]: Okay, I won't ask you what the answer was, but most eligible bachelor in town, ladies,

00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:18.080
[Amit Varma]: if you're listening.

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:24.920
[Guest]: No, so the point is, so yeah, so the larger point is, yeah, I mean, so I was just taking,

00:14:24.920 --> 00:14:27.520
[Guest]: you know, your lingerie point, right?

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:30.240
[Guest]: Or, you know, as we Indians call it, lingerie.

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:33.240
[Amit Varma]: That's not a roundabout revelation that I asked for, right?

00:14:33.240 --> 00:14:39.880
[Guest]: I'll give you a sort of, you know, something that I mean, I mean, I have not, I mean, people

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:46.480
[Guest]: know this, you know, I am extremely fascinated by crime fiction.

00:14:46.480 --> 00:14:51.240
[Guest]: I mean, I read practically, you know, I live to read crime fiction.

00:14:51.240 --> 00:14:57.600
[Guest]: And over the long run, you know, if ever I reach a stage in life where I have some amount

00:14:57.600 --> 00:15:03.680
[Guest]: of f**k you money, I mean, I want to write a crime fiction book, so, which is an ambition

00:15:03.680 --> 00:15:04.680
[Guest]: I share as well.

00:15:04.680 --> 00:15:05.680
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:08.400
[Guest]: So that is, yeah, I guess we can write a crime fiction book.

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:09.400
[Guest]: We can, sorry?

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:10.400
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:11.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, we can sit in.

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:12.400
[Unknown]: No, I mean.

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:19.000
[Guest]: The problem with, you know, the only problem I think is, you know, the plotting etc. is

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:20.000
[Guest]: not a problem.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:27.360
[Guest]: The problem is that, you know, in a city like Bombay, Mumbai, or in any city in India, how

00:15:27.360 --> 00:15:34.160
[Guest]: do you figure out the procedure, part of how, you know, crime gets investigated?

00:15:34.160 --> 00:15:37.520
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, we don't know, I mean, there is nothing really...

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:40.520
[Guest]: But a senior journalist at your level can just get in touch with a cop and say, yeah.

00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:41.520
[Guest]: It's very difficult, yeah.

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:47.360
[Guest]: I mean, so what happens is, so I know someone who was sort of writing a crime fiction book,

00:15:47.360 --> 00:15:56.640
[Guest]: and so she did approach, you know, some senior police guy in Bombay, and so that guy's condition

00:15:56.640 --> 00:15:59.560
[Guest]: was that he also, you know, wanted his name on the book.

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:00.560
[Amit Varma]: So it's not so...

00:16:00.560 --> 00:16:01.560
[Amit Varma]: That's pretty bizarre.

00:16:01.560 --> 00:16:02.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's pretty bizarre.

00:16:02.560 --> 00:16:04.520
[Guest]: So it's not so straightforward, yeah.

00:16:04.520 --> 00:16:07.760
[Guest]: She should put his name on the book just to reveal it to the world, this is the guy.

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:13.720
[Guest]: Or what one could do is, you know, and there are books like that, I mean, if you read the

00:16:13.720 --> 00:16:19.640
[Guest]: Scandinavian crime fiction, you know, especially a guy like Henning Mankal, even though his

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:27.360
[Guest]: books are, you know, the main character, Kurt Wallander, is a chief inspector, he doesn't

00:16:27.360 --> 00:16:29.600
[Guest]: really get into a lot of procedures.

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:33.440
[Guest]: I mean, there's basic shooting, and you know, this gun, that gun, and you know, this is

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:36.000
[Guest]: where the bullet was, and all that's there.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:45.480
[Guest]: But it's more about plotting, and it's more about how Sweden has changed over the years,

00:16:45.480 --> 00:16:51.840
[Guest]: and the politics, you know, of the country and the weather, and it's just...

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:54.600
[Amit Varma]: So you'd do a Bombay analogue of that, if you were to do something.

00:16:54.600 --> 00:16:58.800
[Guest]: In fact, you know, the bizarre thing is, there is no crime fiction set in Bombay.

00:16:58.800 --> 00:17:04.160
[Guest]: I mean, and this is a city that can give you stories dime a dozen.

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:07.480
[Guest]: And this is a city which actually has so many crime reporters.

00:17:07.480 --> 00:17:08.480
[Guest]: And so many stories.

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:09.480
[Amit Varma]: It's mad.

00:17:09.480 --> 00:17:10.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:11.480
[Guest]: And it's so...

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:13.960
[Guest]: I mean, I mean, actually, crime reporters are by far the best guys, you know, when it

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:15.760
[Guest]: comes to writing crime fiction.

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:21.040
[Guest]: I guess the problem in India is that a lot of crime reporters, even though they're very

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:26.760
[Guest]: good reporters, they can't write, you know, so ultimately, they get the story and someone

00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:31.200
[Guest]: they tell the story, and there is a guy sitting and the desk guy in the newspaper actually

00:17:31.200 --> 00:17:32.720
[Guest]: writes out the story.

00:17:32.720 --> 00:17:36.400
[Guest]: So even though they may have the stories, they don't have the ability to...

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:40.080
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, half of any narrative, like a narrative is really either taking a story

00:17:40.080 --> 00:17:41.900
[Amit Varma]: forward or revealing character.

00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:45.720
[Amit Varma]: And I guess a crime reporter would be good at finding out the facts of a story and doing

00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:46.720
[Amit Varma]: that part of it.

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:49.880
[Amit Varma]: But the other half, which is revealing character and going into the depths of human nature...

00:17:49.880 --> 00:17:56.160
[Guest]: In fact, a few years back, you know, Indian Express did a fascinating story on a police

00:17:56.160 --> 00:18:03.480
[Guest]: inspector who has retired, and he cannot let go of a case of a girl who disappeared.

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:07.840
[Guest]: Now, this is just it's such an exciting plot point.

00:18:07.840 --> 00:18:12.360
[Guest]: I mean, you can just start there and then let your imagination flow.

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:15.880
[Guest]: I'm already imagining the back cover of your next book.

00:18:15.880 --> 00:18:22.560
[Guest]: So I mean, I'm just saying, I mean, it's just, I mean, the city has so many stories which

00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:24.560
[Amit Varma]: are not being told.

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:28.440
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, given that you often write about Mr. Modi's economic policies, one could

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:30.520
[Amit Varma]: say you're writing crime nonfiction.

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:35.320
[Amit Varma]: But just moving on from there, now that you've made this splendid revelation and our respective

00:18:35.320 --> 00:18:38.960
[Amit Varma]: Twitter followers should be pleased by it, let's move on to the subject at hand.

00:18:38.960 --> 00:18:43.640
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned Scott Adams earlier, and when we just came to the studio, I saw you reading

00:18:43.640 --> 00:18:49.320
[Amit Varma]: a book by Adams Outside and Adams, of course, writes a brilliant cartoon strip, Dilbert,

00:18:49.320 --> 00:18:52.760
[Amit Varma]: but was surprisingly for a lot of people, disappointingly for a lot of people, a big

00:18:52.760 --> 00:18:54.280
[Amit Varma]: early supporter of Donald Trump.

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:58.520
[Guest]: No, I mean, so, you know, this is a huge misconception that people have.

00:18:58.520 --> 00:19:05.360
[Guest]: I don't think he was he was a supporter, you know, of either Hillary or Donald Trump.

00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:09.880
[Guest]: He basically called the election right early enough.

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:15.720
[Guest]: And he just, you know, he doubled up and he kept going on and on about how Trump will

00:19:15.720 --> 00:19:16.720
[Guest]: win.

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:19.400
[Amit Varma]: And that essentially sort of was...

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:20.400
[Amit Varma]: People thought, oh, he must be a Trump supporter.

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:24.040
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, you know, it's like, you know, in India, now people are talking about the

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:30.080
[Guest]: fact that in 2019, there is no option, the Tina factor to Modi.

00:19:30.080 --> 00:19:35.480
[Guest]: But you know, you there is always an option, you and me may not like that option.

00:19:35.480 --> 00:19:40.680
[Guest]: So I think the situation that Scott Adams was in was very, very similar.

00:19:40.680 --> 00:19:44.240
[Guest]: I mean, he sort of called the election very early.

00:19:44.240 --> 00:19:49.200
[Guest]: And he just stood by it and people did not and I mean, the media by large, especially

00:19:49.200 --> 00:19:53.340
[Guest]: the New York based media, which is liberal did not like that.

00:19:53.340 --> 00:20:01.260
[Amit Varma]: So why I bought Adams up was to seek seamlessly to the subject of Trump, and to the subject

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:07.560
[Amit Varma]: of Trump's vision of the world, which is where, in a sense, our talk about today's episode

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:11.720
[Amit Varma]: comes from, because it seems that he doesn't understand any of the things that you've written

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:17.160
[Amit Varma]: in your book, Easy Money, obviously, but also that his insular view of the world that is

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:20.160
[Amit Varma]: immigrants are bad trade with other countries is bad.

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:22.280
[Amit Varma]: It's just fundamentally flawed.

00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:27.840
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, I've given one basic at the start of this episode, one basic economic

00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:33.120
[Amit Varma]: point of view about why his fulmination against trade deficits are misguided, because I actually

00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:35.040
[Amit Varma]: think trade deficits aren't a bad thing at all.

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:41.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, it's just it's trade benefits everybody, both parties, but you've outlined a somewhat

00:20:41.840 --> 00:20:47.360
[Amit Varma]: deeper monetarist view in your Easy Money trilogy, specifically the third book, the

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:52.280
[Amit Varma]: second last chapter, where you deal explicitly with this and you give historical parallels

00:20:52.280 --> 00:20:53.560
[Amit Varma]: as well.

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:55.920
[Guest]: So can you outline some of this?

00:20:55.920 --> 00:21:01.400
[Guest]: So basically, you know, the first thing we need to realize is as to why is Trump doing

00:21:01.400 --> 00:21:02.400
[Guest]: what he's doing?

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:07.440
[Guest]: I mean, you know, at a superficial level, it seems bizarre, but actually it isn't because

00:21:07.440 --> 00:21:10.360
[Guest]: he's just catering to his audience.

00:21:10.360 --> 00:21:17.580
[Guest]: So when Trump's campaign started, his slogan was, make America great again.

00:21:17.580 --> 00:21:23.080
[Guest]: And the funny thing is that this was not an original slogan at all, because in 1980, Ronald

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:26.400
[Guest]: Reagan had run on the slogan, let's make America great again.

00:21:26.400 --> 00:21:28.760
[Amit Varma]: So Trump simply just dropped one word.

00:21:28.760 --> 00:21:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Reagan, of course, a very different kind of leader and he meant very different things

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:33.000
[Guest]: by it.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.160
[Guest]: He was almost the opposite of what Trump is trying to do.

00:21:36.160 --> 00:21:41.720
[Guest]: So now, you know, why did Trump come up with a slogan like, you know, make America great

00:21:41.720 --> 00:21:42.720
[Guest]: again?

00:21:42.720 --> 00:21:47.800
[Guest]: And this essentially, the answer to this question lies in the fact that, you know, during the

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:54.920
[Guest]: heydays of the manufacturing boom in the United States, there were factories all over the

00:21:54.920 --> 00:21:59.480
[Guest]: country and primarily, you know, what is called middle America.

00:21:59.480 --> 00:22:11.160
[Guest]: And these factories gradually sort of, you know, came to a stop and many white male Americans

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:12.680
[Guest]: lost their jobs.

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:20.520
[Guest]: Now, Trump is essentially catering to this audience and, you know, when someone loses

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:27.280
[Guest]: a job, at least in, you know, developed democracies, they have an unemployment alliance and there

00:22:27.280 --> 00:22:30.080
[Guest]: are many other facilities which are available.

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:37.000
[Guest]: But at the end of the day, it's sort of, you know, not having a proper job hurts you personally.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:42.920
[Guest]: So I just like to quote something, you know, from a book called The Wealth of Humans, written

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:45.000
[Guest]: by a gentleman called Ryan Avent.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:51.080
[Guest]: And in this, he says, work is not just the means by which we obtain resources needed

00:22:51.080 --> 00:22:52.920
[Guest]: to put food on the table.

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:56.060
[Guest]: It is also a source of personal identity.

00:22:56.060 --> 00:22:59.040
[Guest]: It helps give structure to our days and our lives.

00:22:59.040 --> 00:23:05.560
[Guest]: It offers the possibility of personal fulfillment that comes from being of use to others and

00:23:05.560 --> 00:23:13.340
[Guest]: is a critical part of the glue that holds society together and smooths its operation.

00:23:13.340 --> 00:23:17.160
[Guest]: So basically what has happened is, you know, all these Americans who have lost jobs over

00:23:17.160 --> 00:23:22.200
[Guest]: the years have essentially started to think or rather, you know, have been thinking for

00:23:22.200 --> 00:23:30.380
[Guest]: a while that it's the Chinese and the other foreign countries which have taken their jobs.

00:23:30.380 --> 00:23:36.240
[Guest]: So this is essentially the perception that prevails and, you know, perception is reality.

00:23:36.240 --> 00:23:40.640
[Guest]: And Trump has essentially played on this perception.

00:23:40.640 --> 00:23:46.320
[Guest]: So when he says that, you know, make America great again, what he essentially meant was

00:23:46.320 --> 00:23:50.640
[Guest]: that, you know, all these factories which are flourishing, you know, up until the 80s

00:23:50.640 --> 00:23:55.920
[Guest]: and the 90s will come back and, you know, the average American who's lost his job will

00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:58.160
[Guest]: find a job all over again.

00:23:58.160 --> 00:24:03.240
[Guest]: Now, there are a couple of points here which, you know, we need to understand.

00:24:03.240 --> 00:24:09.640
[Guest]: You know, one is that have, you know, the Americans lost their jobs only due to the

00:24:09.640 --> 00:24:14.580
[Guest]: Chinese and, you know, other countries like, you know, Bangladesh, Vietnam, Thailand, Indonesia

00:24:14.580 --> 00:24:19.520
[Guest]: producing goods cheaply than America does?

00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:21.780
[Guest]: The answer is yes and no.

00:24:21.780 --> 00:24:26.800
[Guest]: So what has also happened is that the productivity of the American worker has increased over

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:27.980
[Guest]: the years.

00:24:27.980 --> 00:24:33.840
[Guest]: And there's some research carried out by an economist called Michael Hicks, who writes

00:24:33.840 --> 00:24:40.560
[Guest]: that almost 88% of job losses in manufacturing in America in recent years can be attributed

00:24:40.560 --> 00:24:43.320
[Guest]: to productivity growth of American factories.

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:49.060
[Guest]: Now, in simple terms, what it basically means is that an average American worker is producing

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:53.320
[Guest]: more goods while working in a factory than he did in the past, okay.

00:24:53.320 --> 00:24:56.540
[Guest]: And this is because of advances made in automation and IT.

00:24:56.540 --> 00:24:59.960
[Guest]: It has also led to the need for fewer factories carrying out manufacturing.

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:06.840
[Guest]: Now, one of the data points that Hicks gives is that if the productivity levels of 2000

00:25:06.840 --> 00:25:13.520
[Guest]: had prevailed in 2010, US would have required 20.9 million manufacturing workers.

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:18.240
[Guest]: Instead, the American factories employed only 12.1 million individuals.

00:25:18.240 --> 00:25:24.400
[Guest]: So obviously, there is a gap of close to, you know, 9 million jobs.

00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:29.920
[Guest]: So you know, one reason that why America has lost jobs is because productivity has improved.

00:25:29.920 --> 00:25:35.240
[Guest]: And obviously, given the fact that, you know, other countries can produce things cheaply

00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:38.520
[Guest]: than America can, I mean, has had an impact.

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:44.960
[Guest]: So Trump has essentially, you know, sort of feeded into this sentiment.

00:25:44.960 --> 00:25:51.560
[Guest]: And, you know, one of the things that he said early enough was that he'll try and shrink

00:25:51.560 --> 00:25:53.400
[Guest]: the American trade deficit.

00:25:53.400 --> 00:25:55.880
[Guest]: Now, what does that mean?

00:25:55.880 --> 00:26:00.240
[Guest]: You know, trade deficit, a country runs a trade deficit, essentially, when its imports

00:26:00.240 --> 00:26:02.380
[Guest]: are more than its exports.

00:26:02.380 --> 00:26:07.040
[Guest]: So what Trump basically wanted to say was that he'll sort of try shrinking American

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:09.220
[Guest]: imports.

00:26:09.220 --> 00:26:11.480
[Guest]: How do you shrink American imports?

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:17.960
[Guest]: You shrink American imports by basically encouraging protectionism so that, you know, Americans

00:26:17.960 --> 00:26:21.640
[Guest]: are not able to import goods from other countries.

00:26:21.640 --> 00:26:27.360
[Guest]: And that essentially leads to a situation where, you know, the American companies become

00:26:27.360 --> 00:26:32.000
[Guest]: competitive and they produce goods, which Americans can then buy.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:37.440
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I wrote a column when Trump was running pointing out that he had one thing

00:26:37.440 --> 00:26:43.160
[Amit Varma]: in common with a lot of populist demagogues, which is that he tended to come up with simple,

00:26:43.160 --> 00:26:49.140
[Amit Varma]: easy to understand answers to complex questions, which actually only had complex answers.

00:26:49.140 --> 00:26:53.240
[Amit Varma]: So for example, his answer to the question of where are the jobs in Middle America going

00:26:53.240 --> 00:26:54.460
[Amit Varma]: was twofold.

00:26:54.460 --> 00:26:58.040
[Amit Varma]: One is that your jobs are being shipped out.

00:26:58.040 --> 00:27:00.460
[Amit Varma]: And the other was that immigrants are coming and taking your job.

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:06.920
[Amit Varma]: So therefore, his anti-immigrant and anti-free trade kind of line, both of which are absolutely

00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:07.920
[Amit Varma]: wrong.

00:27:07.920 --> 00:27:10.560
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to now ask you to obviously to expand on the trade deficit.

