00:29:06.400 --> 00:29:07.400
[Guest]: Yes.

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:12.500
[Guest]: So Trump essentially, so this is something that, you know, Peter Navarro says Trump proposes

00:29:12.500 --> 00:29:18.240
[Guest]: eliminating America's trade deficit through a combination of increased exports and reduced

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:19.240
[Guest]: imports.

00:29:19.240 --> 00:29:25.320
[Guest]: The idea is to manufacture more stuff in the US, bring down imports and increase exports.

00:29:25.320 --> 00:29:29.480
[Guest]: In the process, more jobs will be created for America and Americans.

00:29:29.480 --> 00:29:34.120
[Guest]: And this will make America great again, you know, QED, as you said, simple solutions to

00:29:34.120 --> 00:29:35.120
[Unknown]: complex problems.

00:29:35.120 --> 00:29:44.640
[Guest]: And in fact, his website, this is Donald Trump's website, puts it, he plans to direct the Secretary

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:48.440
[Guest]: of Commerce to identify every violation of trade agreements of foreign countries currently

00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:52.840
[Guest]: using to harm our workers and also direct all appropriate agencies to use every tool

00:29:52.840 --> 00:29:56.000
[Guest]: under American and international law to end these abuses.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:01.080
[Guest]: So again, you know, simple things that will sort of put tariffs on goods from abroad,

00:30:01.080 --> 00:30:03.880
[Guest]: you know, and so on and so forth.

00:30:03.880 --> 00:30:12.320
[Guest]: The problem is that what people don't understand is that if you look at American imports and

00:30:12.320 --> 00:30:15.880
[Guest]: American exports, they move almost in a parallel line.

00:30:15.880 --> 00:30:22.720
[Guest]: I mean, even though there is a gap between them, if you were to plot out, you know, the

00:30:22.720 --> 00:30:27.880
[Guest]: imports and the exports of America over the years, you would get two curves, which are

00:30:27.880 --> 00:30:28.880
[Guest]: almost moving.

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:30.800
[Amit Varma]: So there's a positive correlation.

00:30:30.800 --> 00:30:37.800
[Guest]: In fact, if you were to sort of put it in slightly, you know, complex terms, the curves

00:30:37.800 --> 00:30:40.040
[Guest]: have a correlation of close to one.

00:30:40.040 --> 00:30:41.040
[Guest]: Okay.

00:30:41.040 --> 00:30:43.280
[Guest]: Now, what does that essentially mean?

00:30:43.280 --> 00:30:51.280
[Guest]: Now, it basically means that dollars earned by the countries which export goods and services

00:30:51.280 --> 00:30:56.040
[Guest]: to the United States, which is essentially the imports of U.S., are used to buy goods

00:30:56.040 --> 00:30:59.740
[Guest]: and services being exported by the U.S.

00:30:59.740 --> 00:31:03.000
[Guest]: So the imports and the exports are very closely linked.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:08.840
[Guest]: So the moment you crack down on American imports, the other countries, the money that they make

00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:11.140
[Guest]: will come down in the process.

00:31:11.140 --> 00:31:17.480
[Guest]: So they will have lesser money to buy goods and services being exported by the U.S.

00:31:17.480 --> 00:31:22.560
[Guest]: So Trump's view of, you know, simplistic view of sort of decreasing imports and increasing

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:25.320
[Guest]: exports wouldn't work.

00:31:25.320 --> 00:31:26.320
[Guest]: Okay.

00:31:26.320 --> 00:31:30.980
[Guest]: And it would also create a lot of problems globally.

00:31:30.980 --> 00:31:35.880
[Amit Varma]: But I would actually assume that that even if dollars won the universal currency of trade,

00:31:35.880 --> 00:31:39.920
[Amit Varma]: so to say, that same correlation would still be there simply because trade is a positive

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:45.080
[Guest]: sum game, both sides are benefiting, and therefore, if you cut down on trade, both sides lose

00:31:45.080 --> 00:31:46.080
[Amit Varma]: that value.

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:49.520
[Amit Varma]: So even if he stopped buying from the Chinese, they'll have less money to buy from us.

00:31:49.520 --> 00:31:51.280
[Guest]: So in any case, there'll be a correlation.

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:56.360
[Guest]: So I mean, forget dollar, I mean, you know, even let's say if trade was happening in gold

00:31:56.360 --> 00:32:03.760
[Guest]: or, you know, currencies convertible into gold, anything, the same, you know, thing

00:32:03.760 --> 00:32:04.760
[Guest]: would result.

00:32:04.760 --> 00:32:11.560
[Guest]: Now, you know, other than impacting America, this would also impact the global economy

00:32:11.560 --> 00:32:13.440
[Guest]: in a big way.

00:32:13.440 --> 00:32:18.680
[Guest]: And I just like to quote something that an economist named Richard Duncan, you know,

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:21.440
[Guest]: has been talking about over the years.

00:32:21.440 --> 00:32:27.320
[Guest]: What he says is that over the past 35 years, the deficit, which is basically the American

00:32:27.320 --> 00:32:31.640
[Guest]: trade deficit, has become the driver of global economic growth.

00:32:31.640 --> 00:32:32.640
[Guest]: Okay.

00:32:32.640 --> 00:32:37.480
[Guest]: So what will happen if Trump makes it difficult for the United States to import stuff from

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:39.680
[Guest]: China and other parts of the world?

00:32:39.680 --> 00:32:45.080
[Guest]: If the American imports decline, so will its exports, primarily because other countries,

00:32:45.080 --> 00:32:48.360
[Guest]: as you know, said, we said, won't have the dollars required to import stuff from the

00:32:48.360 --> 00:32:49.360
[Guest]: US.

00:32:49.360 --> 00:32:57.480
[Guest]: Also, with both imports, as well as export shrinking, the trade deficit may not reduce,

00:32:57.480 --> 00:32:58.480
[Amit Varma]: right?

00:32:58.480 --> 00:33:01.080
[Amit Varma]: In percentage terms, it might just stay the same.

00:33:01.080 --> 00:33:07.320
[Guest]: So even in non percentage terms, I mean, both your, you know, exports and imports fall by

00:33:07.320 --> 00:33:11.800
[Guest]: the same amount, your trade deficit stays the same, which mind you, I mean, our case

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:13.640
[Amit Varma]: completely is that the trade deficit doesn't matter.

00:33:13.640 --> 00:33:14.640
[Amit Varma]: It's not a bad thing.

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:18.680
[Amit Varma]: But even if you happen to assume that it does matter, and you're sitting in Trump's shoes,

00:33:18.680 --> 00:33:20.360
[Amit Varma]: this actually won't affect it at all.

00:33:20.360 --> 00:33:24.680
[Amit Varma]: So it's ineptitude upon ineptitude, basically.

00:33:24.680 --> 00:33:32.160
[Guest]: Now, further a fall in American imports will mean a fall in global demand.

00:33:32.160 --> 00:33:34.200
[Guest]: And in the process, the global economy will shrink.

00:33:34.200 --> 00:33:35.800
[Guest]: Now, how will this play out?

00:33:35.800 --> 00:33:40.560
[Guest]: Now, Duncan essentially says that any attempt to eliminate the American trade deficit could

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:45.520
[Guest]: easily cause major problems for the global economy leading to another Great Depression.

00:33:45.520 --> 00:33:47.680
[Guest]: Things could go particularly bad for China.

00:33:47.680 --> 00:33:54.520
[Guest]: Now, in 2015, the US ran a trade deficit of $367 billion with China.

00:33:54.520 --> 00:34:00.600
[Guest]: I think in 2017, the number was close to around $336 billion.

00:34:00.600 --> 00:34:05.560
[Guest]: So this essentially means a trade deficit of $1 billion per day, roughly.

00:34:05.560 --> 00:34:11.240
[Guest]: Now, if this deficit is eliminated, you know, the Chinese economy will sort of collapse.

00:34:11.240 --> 00:34:17.600
[Guest]: If China collapses, economies of China's major trading partners will be severely impacted.

00:34:17.600 --> 00:34:21.560
[Guest]: When China exports less, it also imports less, largely because it will have fewer dollars

00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:22.920
[Guest]: to pay for imports.

00:34:22.920 --> 00:34:30.000
[Guest]: Now, this will lead to the Chinese import of commodities from all over the world falling.

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:34.240
[Guest]: This can have a huge impact on commodity exporting countries like Australia and Brazil, to name

00:34:34.240 --> 00:34:35.240
[Guest]: a few.

00:34:35.240 --> 00:34:40.120
[Guest]: Now, Duncan also says that this could lead to social instability in China, threatening

00:34:40.120 --> 00:34:45.080
[Guest]: the rule of the Communist Party, and even military conflict between China and its neighbors

00:34:45.080 --> 00:34:47.240
[Guest]: and the US, possibly.

00:34:47.240 --> 00:34:51.360
[Guest]: The response from China could be like the way Japan responded at Pearl Harbor after

00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:56.080
[Guest]: the United States imposed oil embargo on the country in 1941.

00:34:56.080 --> 00:35:04.640
[Guest]: So the point is that, you know, the US imports have sort of become, you know, a very important

00:35:04.640 --> 00:35:07.120
[Guest]: factor in global demand.

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:12.480
[Guest]: And if those imports are cracked down on, it will impact global demand everywhere.

00:35:12.480 --> 00:35:16.400
[Guest]: And once you know that happens, it could lead to political repercussions.

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and you know, I'd also sum it up simply by saying that, once you understand that trade

00:35:22.960 --> 00:35:28.800
[Amit Varma]: is a positive sum game, and if there's a given state of trade happening between US and China,

00:35:28.800 --> 00:35:32.720
[Amit Varma]: by cutting it down, you're effectively creating a negative sum game where both sides lose

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:33.720
[Amit Varma]: value.

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And because these are two giant economies, and the whole of the world is so dependent

00:35:37.600 --> 00:35:41.040
[Amit Varma]: on these two, it's going to have a ripple effect.

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:44.560
[Amit Varma]: And it's even simplistic to say that China will be the loser here.

00:35:44.560 --> 00:35:49.480
[Amit Varma]: If China loses, we all lose, if America loses, we all lose, if Pakistan loses, we all lose.

00:35:49.480 --> 00:35:53.640
[Amit Varma]: In terms of trade, if anyone is worse off, we are all worse off because the world is

00:35:53.640 --> 00:35:54.640
[Guest]: interlinked.

00:35:54.640 --> 00:35:55.920
[Amit Varma]: You're right.

00:35:55.920 --> 00:36:00.480
[Amit Varma]: So Vivek, before the show started, when I asked you what you do to entertain yourself,

00:36:00.480 --> 00:36:03.320
[Amit Varma]: you said you spend a lot of time on Donald Trump's Twitter feed.

00:36:03.320 --> 00:36:05.720
[Amit Varma]: Give me an update what's going on, man.

00:36:05.720 --> 00:36:11.840
[Guest]: So you know, talking about tweets, Donald Trump recently sent out two tweets.

00:36:11.840 --> 00:36:16.400
[Guest]: One was against Canada, and there's another one, which we'll talk about later.

00:36:16.400 --> 00:36:21.520
[Guest]: So he essentially, you know, in this tweet said, fair trade is now to be called fool

00:36:21.520 --> 00:36:24.160
[Guest]: trade if it is not reciprocal.

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:27.880
[Guest]: According to a Canada release, they make almost $100 billion in trade with the US.

00:36:27.880 --> 00:36:29.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I don't know what he meant.

00:36:29.400 --> 00:36:30.400
[Amit Varma]: It was pretty bizarre.

00:36:30.400 --> 00:36:31.400
[Amit Varma]: I don't think he knew.

00:36:31.400 --> 00:36:32.400
[Guest]: He knows what he meant.

00:36:32.400 --> 00:36:37.280
[Guest]: So what I, you know, once I sort of saw this tweet, I went looking for numbers.

00:36:37.280 --> 00:36:44.360
[Guest]: And very, very surprisingly, what I found was that the United States runs a trade surplus

00:36:44.360 --> 00:36:46.720
[Guest]: of 8.4 billion with Canada.

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:52.920
[Guest]: What it basically means is that the American exports to Canada are greater than the American

00:36:52.920 --> 00:36:54.480
[Guest]: imports from Canada.

00:36:54.480 --> 00:36:58.800
[Amit Varma]: So therefore, by Trump's logic, which we disagree with, if China is screwing America, America

00:36:58.800 --> 00:36:59.800
[Guest]: is screwing Canada.

00:36:59.800 --> 00:37:00.800
[Guest]: Canada.

00:37:00.800 --> 00:37:01.800
[Guest]: Right.

00:37:01.800 --> 00:37:04.840
[Guest]: And any more than that, you know, when you're running a trade surplus with a country, why

00:37:04.840 --> 00:37:05.840
[Guest]: are you even complaining?

00:37:05.840 --> 00:37:06.840
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:37:06.840 --> 00:37:07.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if you're running a trade deficit also, why are you even complaining?

00:37:07.840 --> 00:37:08.840
[Guest]: No, I mean, that's a different thing.

00:37:08.840 --> 00:37:12.200
[Guest]: But I'm just talking from, you know, Trump's logic.

00:37:12.200 --> 00:37:15.880
[Amit Varma]: If a guy thinks the deficit is bad, why would he think a surplus is also bad?

00:37:15.880 --> 00:37:21.240
[Guest]: So, you know, and interestingly, so again, I mean, I looked, once I started looking at

00:37:21.240 --> 00:37:22.240
[Amit Varma]: numbers...

00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:24.680
[Amit Varma]: I think Justin Trudeau is not macho enough for him.

00:37:24.680 --> 00:37:25.680
[Amit Varma]: He's too metrosexual.

00:37:25.680 --> 00:37:29.280
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, that's why Trump likes Kim, big authoritarian dude.

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:33.280
[Guest]: He's like, he likes these macho guys who will go people executing like that.

00:37:33.280 --> 00:37:38.560
[Guest]: So there's this photograph going around, I mean, obviously, it's photoshopped, where...

00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:40.560
[Guest]: All photographs are photoshopped.

00:37:40.560 --> 00:37:43.240
[Guest]: These days, yes, all photographs are photoshopped.

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:49.200
[Guest]: So I mean, so there's this picture going around in which you have Donald Trump marrying Kim.

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:57.880
[Guest]: So anyway, so sort of, you know, I started digging, you know, a little more and realized

00:37:57.880 --> 00:38:04.200
[Guest]: that the United States actually runs a trade deficit with Canada when it comes to goods.

00:38:04.200 --> 00:38:06.720
[Guest]: The trade deficit is around $17 billion.

00:38:06.720 --> 00:38:14.360
[Guest]: But when it comes to services, because, you know, America has, you know, big banks and

00:38:14.360 --> 00:38:18.680
[Guest]: a lot of Canadian tourists actually come to America and spend money.

00:38:18.680 --> 00:38:22.640
[Guest]: America runs a trade surplus with Canada when it comes to services.

00:38:22.640 --> 00:38:25.560
[Guest]: And that surplus is around $25.4 billion.

00:38:25.560 --> 00:38:30.100
[Guest]: And hence, net-net, the overall surplus is around $8.4 billion.

00:38:30.100 --> 00:38:34.080
[Guest]: So the first question is, why is Trump even, you know, what is he complaining about when

00:38:34.080 --> 00:38:39.000
[Guest]: you know, the second thing is that obviously, you know, given the fact that on the whole

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:45.160
[Guest]: America runs a trade deficit, examples like Canada are there.

00:38:45.160 --> 00:38:50.560
[Guest]: In fact, if you look at the American trade deficit, China accounts for nearly three fourths

00:38:50.560 --> 00:38:51.560
[Amit Varma]: of it.

00:38:51.560 --> 00:38:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:53.560
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:38:53.560 --> 00:38:54.560
[Guest]: So it was much less a few years ago.

00:38:54.560 --> 00:38:55.560
[Guest]: Yes.

00:38:55.560 --> 00:39:02.280
[Guest]: So it's it's sort of gone up from around 22% in 2000 to around almost 75% now, which is

00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:08.520
[Amit Varma]: a sign of China's growing manufacturing might and you know, which if not for our labor laws

00:39:08.520 --> 00:39:12.560
[Amit Varma]: and our law, you know, mad regulations, we could have had part of that.

00:39:12.560 --> 00:39:13.560
[Guest]: Yes.

00:39:13.560 --> 00:39:19.240
[Guest]: So the larger point here is that, you know, there's no point bullying Canada, right?

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:21.720
[Guest]: If you have to bully, bully China.

00:39:21.720 --> 00:39:23.800
[Amit Varma]: So he's wasting his time on Canada.

00:39:23.800 --> 00:39:28.760
[Amit Varma]: I think he must have opened Melania's laptop and found a folder there called Justin.

00:39:28.760 --> 00:39:29.760
[Guest]: That must have started him off.

00:39:29.760 --> 00:39:30.760
[Guest]: I'm sorry.

00:39:30.760 --> 00:39:31.760
[Guest]: Continue.

00:39:31.760 --> 00:39:32.760
[Guest]: That was a bad joke.

00:39:32.760 --> 00:39:41.760
[Guest]: So, so if you look at the American trade with China, America runs a trade deficit of $376

00:39:41.760 --> 00:39:47.920
[Guest]: billion when it comes to goods, but it runs a surplus of $40 billion when it comes to

00:39:47.920 --> 00:39:48.920
[Guest]: services.

00:39:48.920 --> 00:39:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:39:49.920 --> 00:39:51.440
[Guest]: So services are for America's doing pretty good.

00:39:51.440 --> 00:39:56.600
[Guest]: It is, you know, it is by far, you know, the most innovative country in the world.

00:39:56.600 --> 00:40:03.800
[Guest]: So now the point is, you know, the point that I want to make here is that, you know, most

00:40:03.800 --> 00:40:08.520
[Guest]: of the global trade happens in terms of dollars.

00:40:08.520 --> 00:40:09.520
[Guest]: Okay.

00:40:09.520 --> 00:40:10.520
[Guest]: And I have a number here.

00:40:10.520 --> 00:40:13.520
[Guest]: I think, let me just look it up.

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:15.620
[Guest]: Yes.

00:40:15.620 --> 00:40:22.280
[Guest]: So this is something from a book called The Scandal of Money, in which George Gilder,

00:40:22.280 --> 00:40:27.840
[Guest]: who's the author says, today, the dollar handles more than 60% of the world trade, denominates

00:40:27.840 --> 00:40:33.600
[Guest]: more than half of the market capitalization of world stocks, and partakes in 87% of global

00:40:33.600 --> 00:40:35.040
[Guest]: currency trades.

00:40:35.040 --> 00:40:41.520
[Guest]: So given the fact that most, you know, global trade is happening in dollars, countries end

00:40:41.520 --> 00:40:42.520
[Guest]: up with dollars, right?

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:46.320
[Guest]: You know, when they trade, they end up with dollars.

00:40:46.320 --> 00:40:48.280
[Guest]: And what do they do with these dollars?

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:53.280
[Guest]: I mean, when you export, you earn dollars, and then you use those dollars to pay for

00:40:53.280 --> 00:40:56.160
[Guest]: imports.

00:40:56.160 --> 00:41:02.560
[Guest]: Beyond that, there is still, you know, countries like China's, because their imports are significantly

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:05.720
[Guest]: lower than their exports, they end up with surplus dollars.

00:41:05.720 --> 00:41:08.040
[Amit Varma]: What would you do if it was the other way around?

00:41:08.040 --> 00:41:09.920
[Amit Varma]: Would you buy dollars from the market?

00:41:09.920 --> 00:41:10.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:41:10.920 --> 00:41:11.920
[Guest]: Basically.

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:17.920
[Guest]: Or there would be capital coming in, right, which would take care of, which is why, you

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:23.880
[Guest]: know, ultimately, if your current account is negative, your capital account, it has

00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:25.480
[Amit Varma]: to be, has to be in surplus.

00:41:25.480 --> 00:41:26.480
[Guest]: Yeah, absolutely.

00:41:26.480 --> 00:41:29.440
[Amit Varma]: So what does China do with these dollars?

00:41:29.440 --> 00:41:35.600
[Guest]: These dollars ultimately find their way, I mean, a lot of them, not all of them, into

00:41:35.600 --> 00:41:40.800
[Guest]: American are invested in American financial securities, primarily treasury bonds issued

00:41:40.800 --> 00:41:42.080
[Guest]: by the American government.

00:41:42.080 --> 00:41:46.120
[Guest]: Now, treasury bonds are essentially government bonds issued by the American government to

00:41:46.120 --> 00:41:48.240
[Guest]: finance the fiscal deficit.

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:51.640
[Guest]: Fiscal deficit is the difference between what a government earns and what it spends.

00:41:51.640 --> 00:41:54.680
[Amit Varma]: In fact, that is the deficit people should be worried about.

00:41:54.680 --> 00:41:56.000
[Guest]: That's a real problem.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:01.440
[Guest]: So what happens is, and China is not the only country which has these surplus dollars, which

00:42:01.440 --> 00:42:05.600
[Guest]: find their way into the US, right?

00:42:05.600 --> 00:42:12.600
[Guest]: There's Japan, there's Brazil, there's India, there is Saudi Arabia, Ireland, a lot of money

00:42:12.600 --> 00:42:13.600
[Guest]: comes.

00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:15.280
[Amit Varma]: So what's the consequence of this?

00:42:15.280 --> 00:42:20.000
[Guest]: What I'm basically trying to say is that, you know, both China and Japan own treasury

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:22.280
[Guest]: bonds of more than a trillion dollars.

00:42:22.280 --> 00:42:23.280
[Guest]: Okay.

00:42:23.280 --> 00:42:28.160
[Guest]: In case of China, China owns, and this is data as of March 2018, China owned around

00:42:28.160 --> 00:42:33.800
[Guest]: 1.19 trillion dollars worth of treasury bonds, Japan owned around 1.04 trillion.

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:38.040
[Amit Varma]: So for the benefit of our listeners, just elaborate on this.

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:39.040
[Amit Varma]: What are these treasury bonds?

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:40.160
[Amit Varma]: How do they function?

00:42:40.160 --> 00:42:44.000
[Guest]: So treasury bonds are, as I said, you know, issued by the American government, they are

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:48.200
[Guest]: by far the safest financial security in the world.

00:42:48.200 --> 00:42:52.920
[Guest]: And they're safest because primarily American government borrows in dollars.

00:42:52.920 --> 00:42:59.440
[Guest]: And if at all there is a problem, it can simply print those dollars and hand it over to the

00:42:59.440 --> 00:43:01.260
[Amit Varma]: people who had.

00:43:01.260 --> 00:43:05.640
[Amit Varma]: So when you buy these US treasury bonds, you're basically lending money to the US at a certain

00:43:05.640 --> 00:43:06.640
[Guest]: rate.

00:43:06.640 --> 00:43:09.680
[Guest]: So because there is so much demand for US treasury bonds, the American government can

00:43:09.680 --> 00:43:14.600
[Guest]: get away with offering a very low rate of interest on these bonds.

00:43:14.600 --> 00:43:15.600
[Guest]: Okay.

00:43:15.600 --> 00:43:19.760
[Guest]: Now, treasury bonds typically in any country or, you know, government bonds in any country

00:43:19.760 --> 00:43:25.260
[Guest]: sort of act as a benchmark for the entire interest rate scenario in that country.

00:43:25.260 --> 00:43:29.320
[Guest]: So if the treasury bonds offer low interest rates, automatically the, you know, the other

00:43:29.320 --> 00:43:32.840
[Guest]: loan interest rates are also low.

00:43:32.840 --> 00:43:39.800
[Guest]: And as you know, you know, as we all know, that low interest rates are very, very important

00:43:39.800 --> 00:43:41.720
[Guest]: of that great American dream.

00:43:41.720 --> 00:43:46.520
[Guest]: I mean, the American dream is basically nothing but consumerism and it's, it's a euphemistic

00:43:46.520 --> 00:43:49.040
[Guest]: term for consumerism.

00:43:49.040 --> 00:43:56.720
[Guest]: So if all these dollars do not find their way back into the US, the interest rates in

00:43:56.720 --> 00:44:01.000
[Guest]: the US will not be as low as they currently are.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:06.720
[Guest]: So you know, the larger point here is that America has an exorbitant privilege.

00:44:06.720 --> 00:44:07.720
[Amit Varma]: What does that mean?

00:44:07.720 --> 00:44:10.800
[Amit Varma]: So just demystify that if I can stop you for a second.

00:44:10.800 --> 00:44:14.600
[Amit Varma]: Is it the case that because all this money finds its way back to the US and therefore

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:19.840
[Amit Varma]: they have that supply of money to lend that therefore that money is cheap because supply

00:44:19.840 --> 00:44:23.560
[Amit Varma]: is great relative demand and therefore they can charge low interest rates.

00:44:23.560 --> 00:44:24.560
[Guest]: Is that correct?

00:44:24.560 --> 00:44:25.560
[Guest]: Yes.

00:44:25.560 --> 00:44:26.560
[Guest]: Yes.

00:44:26.560 --> 00:44:32.640
[Guest]: So, you know, if Donald Trump starts cracking down on American imports, all these surplus

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:35.640
[Guest]: dollars coming back into the US will not come back to the US.

00:44:35.640 --> 00:44:38.880
[Amit Varma]: And therefore the interest rates for American citizens get higher.

00:44:38.880 --> 00:44:41.000
[Guest]: Interest rates will go up.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:42.000
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:46.160
[Guest]: And if interest rates go up, you know, the entire American dream, which I, as I just

00:44:46.160 --> 00:44:49.040
[Guest]: said, is basically consumerism and nothing else.

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:51.520
[Amit Varma]: Though I have to say I disagree with the word consumerism.

00:44:51.520 --> 00:44:54.440
[Amit Varma]: It's a bogey term, but we won't get into that argument here.

00:44:54.440 --> 00:45:01.000
[Guest]: But I get your point that they'll have less money to spend and it will be a downward spiral.

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:05.960
[Guest]: So essentially, you know, so the larger point here is that Donald Trump is basically attacking

00:45:05.960 --> 00:45:11.920
[Guest]: at the heart of the system that has fueled the American dream.

00:45:11.920 --> 00:45:15.840
[Guest]: And it's a system which has already been sort of weakened by many other factors.

00:45:15.840 --> 00:45:18.080
[Amit Varma]: And he's indirectly making America poor again.

00:45:18.080 --> 00:45:19.080
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:45:19.080 --> 00:45:20.080
[Guest]: I mean, that's that's for sure.

00:45:20.080 --> 00:45:21.360
[Guest]: That's for sure.

00:45:21.360 --> 00:45:27.920
[Guest]: And so, so this was one tweet that, you know, a man, Donald Trump sent out.

00:45:27.920 --> 00:45:31.160
[Guest]: The other tweet that he sent out was very interesting.

00:45:31.160 --> 00:45:36.840
[Guest]: And this he sent out yesterday at 522 p.m. and you know, read it at 523.

00:45:36.840 --> 00:45:37.840
[Guest]: I didn't.

00:45:37.840 --> 00:45:38.840
[Guest]: I didn't.

00:45:38.840 --> 00:45:42.280
[Guest]: Essentially, I was coming out of a meeting and, you know, some random guy on Twitter

00:45:42.280 --> 00:45:46.620
[Guest]: sort of, you know, tagged me on that tweet.

00:45:46.620 --> 00:45:49.800
[Amit Varma]: And that random guy on Twitter is listening right now and saying he's calling me a random

00:45:49.800 --> 00:45:51.440
[Guest]: guy.

00:45:51.440 --> 00:45:58.000
[Guest]: I mean, I don't remember who he was, but yes, so thank you, random guy, for bringing this

00:45:58.000 --> 00:45:59.520
[Guest]: to my notice.

00:45:59.520 --> 00:46:04.840
[Guest]: So what what Mr. Trump tweeted was oil prices are too high.

00:46:04.840 --> 00:46:07.000
[Guest]: OPEC is at it again.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:08.000
[Guest]: OK.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:12.320
[Guest]: Now OPEC, as you know, is the Organization for Petroleum Exporting Countries.

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:20.000
[Guest]: It is an oil cartel, primarily, you know, led by Saudi Arabia.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:24.880
[Guest]: Now, if you attack OPEC, you're basically attacking Saudi Arabia.

00:46:24.880 --> 00:46:28.920
[Guest]: I mean, there are no two ways about it.

00:46:28.920 --> 00:46:34.040
[Guest]: So, you know, so basically, you know, we'll we'll need to get into a little bit of history

00:46:34.040 --> 00:46:35.040
[Guest]: here.

00:46:35.040 --> 00:46:41.240
[Guest]: And before we do that, you know, there is some basic, some, you know, economics that

00:46:41.240 --> 00:46:44.760
[Guest]: I need to sort of share here.

00:46:44.760 --> 00:46:50.040
[Guest]: So OPEC is what economists would call a leading firm model of oligopoly.

00:46:50.040 --> 00:46:51.040
[Guest]: OK.

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:56.480
[Guest]: Now, if you accuse me of using big words, I mean, I know when I first came across this

00:46:56.480 --> 00:47:01.720
[Guest]: terminology, I was like, you know, why can't they just use at least, you know, oligopoly

00:47:01.720 --> 00:47:03.640
[Amit Varma]: could have been coined a little more.

00:47:03.640 --> 00:47:04.640
[Amit Varma]: Can I use OPEC in a sentence?

00:47:04.640 --> 00:47:07.080
[Amit Varma]: Do you know the difference between water and oil?

00:47:07.080 --> 00:47:08.080
[Amit Varma]: No.

00:47:08.080 --> 00:47:09.080
[Amit Varma]: Water is transparent, oil is OPEC.

00:47:09.080 --> 00:47:10.080
[Amit Varma]: Oh, man.

00:47:10.080 --> 00:47:11.080
[Guest]: Sorry.

00:47:11.080 --> 00:47:19.320
[Guest]: So OPEC essentially follows the leading firm model of oligopoly.

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:25.720
[Guest]: And that basically means that they cater to a market dominated by a small number of sellers

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:30.280
[Guest]: and within those small number of sellers, the largest seller, which in this case happens

00:47:30.280 --> 00:47:32.720
[Guest]: to be Saudi Arabia, sets the price.

00:47:32.720 --> 00:47:33.720
[Guest]: OK.

00:47:33.720 --> 00:47:39.440
[Guest]: So why I sort of went into this is to tell our readers that when you attack OPEC, you're

00:47:39.440 --> 00:47:42.400
[Guest]: essentially attacking Saudi Arabia.

00:47:42.400 --> 00:47:44.600
[Guest]: Now, so there is a lot of history.

00:47:44.600 --> 00:47:47.600
[Amit Varma]: Trump may not even know that, but never mind.

00:47:47.600 --> 00:47:49.720
[Guest]: Let's not go there.

00:47:49.720 --> 00:47:56.440
[Guest]: So there's a lot of history that we sort of need to discuss with our listeners here.

00:47:56.440 --> 00:48:05.200
[Guest]: Now, you know, America in the early 20th century fell in love with the automobile and the production

00:48:05.200 --> 00:48:12.000
[Guest]: sort of went up from around 1.9 million units in 1920 to 4.5 million in 1929.

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:17.120
[Guest]: And after that, the Great Depression struck and then the Second World War happened.

00:48:17.120 --> 00:48:22.080
[Guest]: And during the Second World War, all these automobile factories essentially were converted

00:48:22.080 --> 00:48:24.040
[Guest]: into arms factories.

00:48:24.040 --> 00:48:30.760
[Guest]: Now, once the World War started coming to an end, and this was late 1944, early 1945,

00:48:30.760 --> 00:48:35.760
[Guest]: the Americans realized that, you know, there would be an automobile boom all over again

00:48:35.760 --> 00:48:40.320
[Guest]: because, you know, people had not bought cars for many years.

00:48:40.320 --> 00:48:43.880
[Guest]: And what was also happening was that, you know, American cities were expanding, you

00:48:43.880 --> 00:48:50.160
[Guest]: know, all these suburbs were coming in and there was no, you know, public transport system

00:48:50.160 --> 00:48:51.960
[Guest]: to cater to these suburbs.

00:48:51.960 --> 00:48:54.900
[Guest]: So you needed cars.

00:48:54.900 --> 00:49:02.280
[Guest]: So sometime in 1945, the American president, Franklin Roosevelt, you know, realized this.

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:06.360
[Guest]: I mean, obviously, his set of advisors would have told him about it.

00:49:06.360 --> 00:49:12.400
[Guest]: And he traveled quietly to the USS Quincy, a ship anchored in the Red Sea.

00:49:12.400 --> 00:49:17.080
[Guest]: Here he met King Ibn Saud of Saudi Arabia, the country which was by then home to the

00:49:17.080 --> 00:49:20.040
[Guest]: largest oil reserves in the world.

00:49:20.040 --> 00:49:28.840
[Guest]: And American, you know, so basically America, as I said, had become obsessed with the automobile

00:49:28.840 --> 00:49:35.200
[Guest]: and due to that, this had led to a swift decline in its oil reserves, even though it was the

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:38.760
[Guest]: biggest producer of oil at that point of time.

00:49:38.760 --> 00:49:42.240
[Guest]: The country needed to secure another source for an assured supply of oil.

00:49:42.240 --> 00:49:47.040
[Guest]: In return for access to Saudi Arabian oil reserves, King Ibn Saud was promised full

00:49:47.040 --> 00:49:53.880
[Guest]: American military support to the ruling clan of Al Saud, who still rule, who still rule

00:49:53.880 --> 00:49:57.640
[Guest]: and the military guarantee is also still there.

00:49:57.640 --> 00:50:04.200
[Guest]: What had also happened sort of parallelly was that in 1944, the countries, you know,

00:50:04.200 --> 00:50:11.960
[Guest]: the world had gotten together at Bretton Woods in the state of New Hampshire in the United

00:50:11.960 --> 00:50:16.680
[Guest]: States and sort of tried to design a new global monetary system.

00:50:16.680 --> 00:50:22.560
[Guest]: And in this new global monetary system, the American dollar was at the heart.

00:50:22.560 --> 00:50:29.480
[Guest]: It was the only currency that continued to be convertible into gold, you know.

00:50:29.480 --> 00:50:35.080
[Guest]: So you could, countries, other countries could convert their, you know, convert US dollars

00:50:35.080 --> 00:50:37.760
[Guest]: into gold.

00:50:37.760 --> 00:50:43.320
[Guest]: And I think one ounce of gold was essentially worth $35.

00:50:43.320 --> 00:50:48.100
[Guest]: So one ounce is around 31.1 grams.

00:50:48.100 --> 00:50:54.840
[Guest]: So this essentially led to a situation where countries sort of started, you know, till

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:57.680
[Guest]: then the trading currency used to be the British pound.

00:50:57.680 --> 00:51:04.080
[Guest]: Now, countries gradually started moving away from the pound and, you know, graduating towards

00:51:04.080 --> 00:51:09.800
[Guest]: the dollar primarily because pound was no longer convertible into gold and dollar was.

00:51:09.800 --> 00:51:16.120
[Guest]: So this essentially led to a situation where the global trade moved towards dollars.

00:51:16.120 --> 00:51:21.040
[Amit Varma]: And OPEC also, because people felt more secure, because it was convertible, it was convertible

00:51:21.040 --> 00:51:22.040
[Guest]: into gold.

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:28.160
[Guest]: See, paper money as you know, as we sort of discussed in a previous episode is pure paper

00:51:28.160 --> 00:51:37.480
[Guest]: money is a very recent concept, which is probably as old as, you know, 45, 46 years, I mean,

00:51:37.480 --> 00:51:42.200
[Guest]: 71 was when the link between gold and paper money broke down completely.

00:51:42.200 --> 00:51:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And I urge our listeners to go to seen unseen.in where our archives are and check out my episode

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:54.080
[Amit Varma]: on easy money with Vivek, which discussed his books in detail and plus the sort of insights

00:51:54.080 --> 00:51:55.440
[Amit Varma]: he's touching upon right now.

00:51:55.440 --> 00:52:00.800
[Guest]: So so basically, you know, back then everyone sort of wanted their paper currency to be

00:52:00.800 --> 00:52:02.080
[Guest]: convertible into gold.

00:52:02.080 --> 00:52:07.680
[Guest]: So and you know, OPEC was no exception and Saudi Arabia was no exception.

00:52:07.680 --> 00:52:10.040
[Guest]: I mean, the Saudis love their gold.

00:52:10.040 --> 00:52:13.840
[Guest]: So oil was bought and sold in dollars.

00:52:13.840 --> 00:52:14.840
[Guest]: Okay.

00:52:14.840 --> 00:52:21.360
[Guest]: Now, this is a very important point, which a lot of people don't realize oil continues

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:23.200
[Guest]: to be bought and sold in dollars.

00:52:23.200 --> 00:52:30.080
[Guest]: In fact, you know, over the years, other members of the OPEC, including Iran, have tried to

00:52:30.080 --> 00:52:32.960
[Guest]: move OPEC away from dollars.

00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:39.080
[Guest]: I mean, in fact, in the late 70s, you know, few countries wanted to sell oil in a basket

00:52:39.080 --> 00:52:42.400
[Guest]: of currencies, but Saudi Arabia did not let it happen.

00:52:42.400 --> 00:52:46.880
[Amit Varma]: So essentially, if India wants to buy oil from Saudi Arabia or slash OPEC, it will have

00:52:46.880 --> 00:52:50.400
[Amit Varma]: to pay in dollars, and it will have to get those dollars from somewhere.

00:52:50.400 --> 00:52:56.080
[Guest]: So when oil is bought and sold in dollars, it essentially forces countries which do not

00:52:56.080 --> 00:53:00.240
[Guest]: produce enough oil to earn those dollars.

00:53:00.240 --> 00:53:01.760
[Guest]: How do you earn those dollars?

00:53:01.760 --> 00:53:08.720
[Guest]: You earn those dollars by exporting whatever you have in terms of dollars, and then you

00:53:08.720 --> 00:53:11.840
[Guest]: use those dollars to buy this oil.

00:53:11.840 --> 00:53:15.240
[Guest]: And most countries in the world do not produce enough oil.

00:53:15.240 --> 00:53:22.960
[Guest]: I mean, like the Indian import dependency in 2017-18 was close to 82%, which basically

00:53:22.960 --> 00:53:28.520
[Guest]: means that only 18% of the oil consumed in India was produced in India.

00:53:28.520 --> 00:53:30.120
[Guest]: The rest was imported.

00:53:30.120 --> 00:53:33.280
[Guest]: And when you import, you pay in dollars.

00:53:33.280 --> 00:53:36.800
[Guest]: And when you pay in dollars, you need to earn in dollars.

00:53:36.800 --> 00:53:38.880
[Guest]: So again, you know, this goes back to the...

00:53:38.880 --> 00:53:40.200
[Amit Varma]: What's the implication of this?

00:53:40.200 --> 00:53:45.960
[Guest]: So the implication is this, you know, it goes back to a term that I used, exorbitant privilege.

00:53:45.960 --> 00:53:50.440
[Guest]: You know, all other countries in the world need to earn these dollars.

00:53:50.440 --> 00:53:53.840
[Guest]: Saudi Arabia can simply print money, can simply print it.

00:53:53.840 --> 00:54:01.040
[Guest]: So if oil, let's say, is not sold in terms of dollars, what happens then?

00:54:01.040 --> 00:54:05.840
[Guest]: Let's say oil is, you know, I mean, they sort of, the Saudi guys come up with, OPEC comes

00:54:05.840 --> 00:54:11.280
[Guest]: up with its own currency, okay, and says, okay, now we'll only buy and sell oil in this

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:12.280
[Guest]: currency.

00:54:12.280 --> 00:54:13.280
[Amit Varma]: What happens then?

00:54:13.280 --> 00:54:14.280
[Amit Varma]: I would name it Kols.

00:54:14.280 --> 00:54:15.280
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, whatever.

00:54:15.280 --> 00:54:18.280
[Guest]: They may call it Al-Sauds or whatever.

00:54:18.280 --> 00:54:19.280
[Guest]: Al-Kols.

00:54:19.280 --> 00:54:20.280
[Guest]: So what happens then?

00:54:20.280 --> 00:54:23.080
[Guest]: Then the world does not need to trade in dollars.

00:54:23.080 --> 00:54:27.480
[Guest]: If the world does not need to trade in dollars, the world does not need to export in dollars.

00:54:27.480 --> 00:54:34.080
[Guest]: If the world does not need to export in dollars, all the surplus dollars do not go back to

00:54:34.080 --> 00:54:35.080
[Guest]: the US.

00:54:35.080 --> 00:54:36.080
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:54:36.080 --> 00:54:37.080
[Amit Varma]: And this again affects the interest rates.

00:54:37.080 --> 00:54:41.880
[Amit Varma]: And so there are, I mean, the point is there are implications, you know, which you cannot

00:54:41.880 --> 00:54:43.480
[Guest]: possibly even think of.

00:54:43.480 --> 00:54:44.480
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:54:44.480 --> 00:54:49.400
[Amit Varma]: And we are all tied to each other and if you affect this in terms of making trade freer,

00:54:49.400 --> 00:54:52.200
[Amit Varma]: you increase the virtuous cycle effect of it.

00:54:52.200 --> 00:54:56.180
[Amit Varma]: And if you actually cut down on free trade, you can make it a vicious cycle where everybody

00:54:56.180 --> 00:54:59.080
[Amit Varma]: spirals and gets worse.

00:54:59.080 --> 00:55:00.080
[Guest]: Yes.

00:55:00.080 --> 00:55:04.760
[Guest]: So basically, you know, what happens is, and this is again, you know, it all goes back

00:55:04.760 --> 00:55:07.280
[Guest]: to the title of your show, the seen and the unseen.

00:55:07.280 --> 00:55:08.280
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:55:08.280 --> 00:55:09.280
[Amit Varma]: These are all unseen.

00:55:09.280 --> 00:55:14.440
[Guest]: Because what happens is when we talk economics, especially, you know, political economy, we

00:55:14.440 --> 00:55:16.680
[Guest]: just tend to look at the seen effects.

00:55:16.680 --> 00:55:21.360
[Guest]: But there are so many unseen, you know, second order, third order effects that you simply

00:55:21.360 --> 00:55:24.120
[Guest]: cannot figure out in advance.

00:55:24.120 --> 00:55:25.120
[Guest]: Right.

00:55:25.120 --> 00:55:34.040
[Guest]: So, so again, so the larger point here is that, you know, a precedent of, you know,

00:55:34.040 --> 00:55:42.200
[Guest]: of the only global superpower should not be tweeting like, you know, you and me do.

00:55:42.200 --> 00:55:45.400
[Amit Varma]: So I don't tweet like that, I'm very offended by that.

00:55:45.400 --> 00:55:49.240
[Amit Varma]: No, by you and me, I mean, people in general, people in general.

00:55:49.240 --> 00:55:53.880
[Amit Varma]: So Vivek, just to change the subject, when we were talking on the phone yesterday, I

00:55:53.880 --> 00:55:59.440
[Amit Varma]: was recording this on a Thursday before the Monday when it's released.

00:55:59.440 --> 00:56:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the day when the football World Cup starts.

00:56:01.920 --> 00:56:05.760
[Amit Varma]: And I told you that, hey, do you know, Spain has just sacked their coach, Lopeta Aguillo,

00:56:05.760 --> 00:56:07.340
[Amit Varma]: however, his name is pronounced.

00:56:07.340 --> 00:56:09.480
[Amit Varma]: And you started talking about easy money again.

00:56:09.480 --> 00:56:12.560
[Guest]: Iske saath Spain ka kya connection hai?

00:56:12.560 --> 00:56:17.560
[Guest]: So the connection is that, you know, whatever is happening in the US now, has sort of happened

00:56:17.560 --> 00:56:23.800
[Guest]: with the Spain, you know, few centuries back in the 15th and the 16th century.

00:56:23.800 --> 00:56:31.080
[Guest]: So you know, essentially, what happened was that in the early 16th century, Spaniards

00:56:31.080 --> 00:56:35.680
[Guest]: captured large parts of what is now known as South America, right.

00:56:35.680 --> 00:56:40.880
[Guest]: And the area had large deposits of silver and gold, right.

00:56:40.880 --> 00:56:47.800
[Guest]: So these precious metals were sort of transported from Spain, from South America to Spain, and,

00:56:47.800 --> 00:56:50.960
[Guest]: you know, then they were converted into coins.

00:56:50.960 --> 00:56:56.600
[Guest]: And these coins were used to buy things, okay.

00:56:56.600 --> 00:57:03.280
[Guest]: And you know, the story, one of the great stories of this is that in 1545, one of the

00:57:03.280 --> 00:57:10.120
[Guest]: biggest silver mines was found in a place called Potosi, I hope I'm pronouncing it correctly,

00:57:10.120 --> 00:57:11.120
[Guest]: which is now in Bolivia.

00:57:11.120 --> 00:57:16.680
[Guest]: Now Potosi is one of the highest cities in the world and is situated at a height of 4090

00:57:16.680 --> 00:57:17.960
[Guest]: meters.

00:57:17.960 --> 00:57:22.440
[Guest]: And given the altitude that it sits on, it took Spaniards some time to get there.

00:57:22.440 --> 00:57:26.800
[Guest]: Here a mountain of silver of six miles around its base was discovered.

00:57:26.800 --> 00:57:32.920
[Guest]: The mountain or the rich hill as it became to be called, generated nearly 45,000 tons

00:57:32.920 --> 00:57:38.640
[Guest]: of silver between 1556 and 1783, which is like, you know, more than 200 years.

00:57:38.640 --> 00:57:40.960
[Guest]: But that was the original city on a hill.

00:57:40.960 --> 00:57:45.200
[Guest]: And most of this newfound silver was shipped to Spain.

00:57:45.200 --> 00:57:50.060
[Guest]: And in the best years, some 300 tons of silver came in from silver mines in the various parts

00:57:50.060 --> 00:57:53.480
[Guest]: of South America.

00:57:53.480 --> 00:58:00.200
[Guest]: Now once this gold and silver started coming in from, you know, from South America, the

00:58:00.200 --> 00:58:05.000
[Guest]: Spaniards became proficient at spending it rather than engaging themselves in any productive

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:07.000
[Guest]: activity.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:10.760
[Guest]: Easy money had spoiled them and they produced very little of their own.

00:58:10.760 --> 00:58:12.800
[Guest]: Once this happened, everything had to be imported.

00:58:12.800 --> 00:58:18.000
[Guest]: You know, weapons came from the Dutch, woolens from British, glassware from Italians and

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:19.000
[Guest]: so on.

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:25.000
[Guest]: Now Thomas Sowell, you know, who we were discussing at the very beginning, makes a very interesting

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:32.400
[Guest]: point in Wealth, Poverty and Politics, which is, you know, a great book that he's written.

00:58:32.400 --> 00:58:38.800
[Guest]: The vast wealth pouring into Spain allowed the Spanish elite to live in luxury and leisure,

00:58:38.800 --> 00:58:43.100
[Guest]: enjoying the products of other countries purchased with windfall gain in gold and silver.

00:58:43.100 --> 00:58:48.080
[Guest]: At one point, Spanish imports were nearly twice as large as its exports, with the difference

00:58:48.080 --> 00:58:50.560
[Guest]: being covered by payments in gold and silver.

00:58:50.560 --> 00:58:55.560
[Guest]: It was a source of pride, however, that all the world served Spain while Spain served

00:58:55.560 --> 00:58:56.560
[Guest]: nobody.

00:58:56.560 --> 00:59:03.160
[Guest]: Now if you sort of compare the situation, you know, something similar is playing out

00:59:03.160 --> 00:59:04.160
[Guest]: in the US.

00:59:04.160 --> 00:59:08.720
[Guest]: Now obviously things are not as bad in the US as they were in Spain, but if you look

00:59:08.720 --> 00:59:15.280
[Guest]: at the ratio of US imports and US exports, and I'm talking about goods here, not services,

00:59:15.280 --> 00:59:25.440
[Guest]: the ratio is 1.5, which basically means that the US imports 50% more goods than it exports.

00:59:25.440 --> 00:59:33.160
[Guest]: So, you know, Spain had like, you know, Spain had an unlimited amount of access to gold

00:59:33.160 --> 00:59:34.160
[Guest]: and silver.

00:59:34.160 --> 00:59:39.240
[Guest]: Similarly, US has an unlimited access to the dollar, you know, other countries, as we've

00:59:39.240 --> 00:59:40.720
[Amit Varma]: been discussing, need to earn it.

00:59:40.720 --> 00:59:44.560
[Amit Varma]: They can just spend the money, that will devalue their own currency and cause inflation, blah

00:59:44.560 --> 00:59:45.560
[Guest]: blah blah, but whatever.

00:59:45.560 --> 00:59:49.360
[Guest]: Yes, but over a period of time, you know, even if they gradually keep printing it, it

00:59:49.360 --> 00:59:57.560
[Guest]: doesn't make, you know, a rate of inflation of 2-3% a year does not really kill anyone,

00:59:57.560 --> 00:59:58.560
[Guest]: right?

00:59:58.560 --> 01:00:03.560
[Guest]: While the unlimited access to gold and silver was Spain's easy money, the dollar is United

01:00:03.560 --> 01:00:08.560
[Guest]: States' easy money, and given this, it isn't surprising that like Spain, the United States

01:00:08.560 --> 01:00:12.080
[Guest]: imports much more than it exports.

01:00:12.080 --> 01:00:18.160
[Guest]: Also, you know, Spain had to face the risk of gold and silver running out, which it eventually

01:00:18.160 --> 01:00:22.760
[Guest]: did, but the US can keep running its printing press.

01:00:22.760 --> 01:00:24.840
[Amit Varma]: So how did that Spanish story play out?

01:00:24.840 --> 01:00:28.160
[Amit Varma]: I don't know how they'll do at this World Cup, but how did that story play out?

01:00:28.160 --> 01:00:33.480
[Guest]: So obviously, you know, after a point of time, you know, the supply of silver sort of started

01:00:33.480 --> 01:00:34.480
[Guest]: coming down.

01:00:34.480 --> 01:00:38.000
[Guest]: I mean, it peaked in 1600 and started to fall after that.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:42.480
[Guest]: But the spending habits of people did not change immediately, leading to Spain getting

01:00:42.480 --> 01:00:50.160
[Guest]: into debts with foreigners and the government defaulted on its loans, you know, in 1607,

01:00:50.160 --> 01:00:53.040
[Guest]: 1627 and 1647.

01:00:53.040 --> 01:00:56.560
[Guest]: So that's in a sense a crucial difference in that they ran out of gold, the US as well.

01:00:56.560 --> 01:00:59.200
[Guest]: Yes, because what happens is, you know, ultimately at that point of time, you know, gold was

01:00:59.200 --> 01:01:03.240
[Guest]: money and there was no, you know, gold wasn't unlimited.

01:01:03.240 --> 01:01:09.160
[Guest]: The US can never run out of money, as long as dollar continues to be the international

01:01:09.160 --> 01:01:12.600
[Guest]: trading, international reserve currency.

01:01:12.600 --> 01:01:16.360
[Amit Varma]: So tell me something, how do you see all of this playing out?

01:01:16.360 --> 01:01:17.360
[Amit Varma]: You cannot...

01:01:17.360 --> 01:01:18.360
[Amit Varma]: What's your worst case scenario?

01:01:18.360 --> 01:01:19.360
[Amit Varma]: You cannot predict anything.

01:01:19.360 --> 01:01:25.840
[Guest]: I mean, you know, there is no worst case scenario, because something like this can continue for

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:26.840
[Guest]: years and years.

01:01:26.840 --> 01:01:31.640
[Guest]: I mean, it can possibly last, you know, even our lifetimes.

01:01:31.640 --> 01:01:35.840
[Amit Varma]: And we are, you know, sort of in an age of populist demagogues everywhere who are insular

01:01:35.840 --> 01:01:36.840
[Amit Varma]: in this way.

01:01:36.840 --> 01:01:40.520
[Amit Varma]: And if you think about it, this is not really a right-left divide, because people on the

01:01:40.520 --> 01:01:42.960
[Amit Varma]: right typically tend to be for free trade.

01:01:42.960 --> 01:01:47.080
[Amit Varma]: And in this case, if you look at their policies towards trade, Trump and Bernie Sanders have

01:01:47.080 --> 01:01:51.440
[Amit Varma]: pretty much identical and identically destructive policies.

01:01:51.440 --> 01:01:57.760
[Guest]: In fact, you know, the interesting point is, if not the US dollar, then what?

01:01:57.760 --> 01:01:58.760
[Guest]: Okay.

01:01:58.760 --> 01:02:03.880
[Guest]: Now, in 99, when the euro sort of came into the picture, people started to say, okay,

01:02:03.880 --> 01:02:06.240
[Guest]: now the euro will take on the dollar.

01:02:06.240 --> 01:02:15.440
[Guest]: But if you look at the situation in Europe, and especially Southern Europe, it's even,

01:02:15.440 --> 01:02:19.920
[Guest]: you know, more worse than, you know, the situation in the US.

01:02:19.920 --> 01:02:22.440
[Guest]: In fact, the situation in the US has now started to improve.

01:02:22.440 --> 01:02:25.640
[Guest]: So how does the euro challenge the dollar?

01:02:25.640 --> 01:02:30.600
[Guest]: If you look at Japan, I mean, the country has not grown for many, many years.

01:02:30.600 --> 01:02:36.560
[Guest]: And with the number of old people going up and the population shrinking, whether the

01:02:36.560 --> 01:02:40.320
[Guest]: country will, you know, what will happen is anybody's guess.

01:02:40.320 --> 01:02:42.880
[Guest]: So again, the yen cannot take on the dollar.

01:02:42.880 --> 01:02:45.940
[Guest]: That leaves us with the Chinese Yuan.

01:02:45.940 --> 01:02:53.080
[Guest]: The Chinese Yuan cannot take on the dollar until China has full capital account convertibility.

01:02:53.080 --> 01:02:55.120
[Guest]: Now, what do I mean by that?

01:02:55.120 --> 01:03:01.440
[Guest]: What I mean is that a Chinese guy can sort of take out his money from China and invest

01:03:01.440 --> 01:03:03.760
[Guest]: it anywhere in the world at any point of time.

01:03:03.760 --> 01:03:09.200
[Guest]: Now, that is not allowed as of now, because China needs access to all these savings to

01:03:09.200 --> 01:03:11.880
[Guest]: build all the infrastructure that it is.

01:03:11.880 --> 01:03:18.720
[Guest]: So if, you know, if money cannot sort of flow in and flow out freely from any country at

01:03:18.720 --> 01:03:22.640
[Guest]: any point of time, that currency can never be the international reserve currency.

01:03:22.640 --> 01:03:28.160
[Guest]: You know, major reason why dollar is the international reserve currency is because the US Treasury

01:03:28.160 --> 01:03:30.440
[Guest]: bond market is extremely liquid.

01:03:30.440 --> 01:03:34.200
[Guest]: You can bring in money at any point of time, you can take out money at any point of time.

01:03:34.200 --> 01:03:37.800
[Guest]: So which means they'll continue to have a disproportionately large influence on the

01:03:37.800 --> 01:03:38.800
[Guest]: world's economy.

01:03:38.800 --> 01:03:42.880
[Guest]: So what will happen is, my guess is, since you've asked me to sort of paint a futuristic

01:03:42.880 --> 01:03:48.720
